Following the method given in section 4.9.1, we need to calculate the probabilities of obtaining 0, 1, or 2 pints of group B blood. We thus need to calculate the number of ways of choosing these numbers from a sample of 100, which are:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& {\left[\begin{array}{l} 0 \\ 0 \end{array}\right]=1} \\
& {\left[\begin{array}{l} 0 \\ 1 \end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{l} 0 \\ 0 \end{array}\right] \times 100 / 1=100} \\
& {\left[\begin{array}{l} 0 \\ 2 \end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{l} 0 \\ 1 \end{array}\right] \times 99 / 2=4950}
\end{aligned}
$$

Using the formula in section 4.9.1, the required probability is

$$
\begin{aligned}
& (0.08)^0(0.92)^{100}+100(0.08)^1(0.92)^{99}+4950(0.08)^2(0.92)^{98} \\
& =0.00024+0.00208+0.00895=0.0113
\end{aligned}
$$

The probability of getting fewer than three pints of group B blood is about 1 in 100, or 0.01.
